text.tspan: Lane Closure on a Two-Lane Road Using Temporary Traffc Control Signals
Temporary traffc control signals shall be installed and operated in accordance with the provisions
of Part 4. Temporary traffc control signals shall meet the physical display and operational
requirements of conventional traffc control signals.
2. Temporary traffc control signal timing shall be established by authorized offcials. Durations of red
clearance intervals shall be adequate to clear the one-lane section of conficting vehicles.
When the temporary traffc control signal is changed to the fashing mode, either manually or
automatically, red signal indications shall be fashed to both approaches.
Stop lines shall be installed with temporary traffc control signals for long-term closures. Existing
conficting pavement markings and raised pavement marker refectors between the activity area
and each stop line shall be removed. After the temporary traffc control signal is removed, the stop
lines and other temporary pavement markings shall be removed and the permanent pavement
Safeguards shall be incorporated to avoid the possibility of conficting signal indications at each end
6. Where no-passing lines are not already in place, they should be added.
7. Adjustments in the location of the advance warning signs should be made as needed to accommodate the
horizontal or vertical alignment of the roadway, recognizing that the distances shown for sign spacings
are minimums. Adjustments in the height of the signal heads should be made as needed to conform to the
Positive protection devices may be used per Section 6M.02.

Removable pavement markings may be used.
